# If Not, Then...

`else` runs code when the `if` condition is false.

```php
if (condition) {
    // true case
} else {
    // false case
}
```

```php
<?php
$age = 16;

if ($age >= 18) {
    echo "Adult";
} else {
    echo "Minor";
}

// Output: Minor
?>
```

# Chaining Conditions

If you have more than two paths, use `elseif`.

```php
if (condition1) {
    // condition1 true
} elseif (condition2) {
    // condition1 false, condition2 true
} else {
    // all false
}
```

You can have many `elseif`s. PHP stops at the first true condition.

```php
<?php
$score = 85;

if ($score >= 90) {
    echo "A";
} elseif ($score >= 80) {
    echo "B";
} elseif ($score >= 70) {
    echo "C";
} else {
    echo "F";
}

// Output: B
?>
```

